82 builder2~
The quick and easy guide to building.
General note: when editing descriptions and using the . command
(like .f) you need to have parsing turned off on programs such as zmud, this can be 
done by clicking on the little computer screen n the corner and placing the cross on it 
(this also disables stringing commands together using the ; )
 
Before you start, make sure you have a rough map of the shape, the number of rooms 
and where the doors are going to be in your area, otherwise you will get into all sorts 
of trouble.
 
Type asave area A LOT, otherwise your area will eventually become corrupted t some 
point, and ALWAYS type it before you log out.
 
In general for your first area think small, no more then 30 rooms, otherwise it will 
never get finished.
 
REDIT
 
Step 1, ignore and don't think about mprogs for your first area.
 
Step 2, remember you area name, if you forgot use alist to list all areas.
 
Step 3, creating rooms: Use redit <vnum> to edit a room (this also transfers you 
directly into that room). Or use redit create <vnum> to add a new room.
Typing command gives you a list of all the commands now available to you in redit. 
Typing show shows all the room details in redit.
 
Step 4, start typing: typing desc allows you to edit the room's description (typing 
description edits your own description not the rooms). Your descriptions need to be at 
least 4 lines long, and don't mention names of the mobs you will create (as they could 
be killed and then the description looks odd), physical objects that will be in the room 
that are takeable (again if there taken it looks odd). A little colour can make the room 
a bit more alive, but try to avoid too much. Use help colour for a list of available 
colours (it is also necessary to terminate all colours at the end of the colour section 
with {x.
 
Step 5, exits, use help exit for more information. To add an exit, you need to still be in 
redit, use either dig which creates the new room as well as linking it, or link. 
Type <direction> dig <vnum>  
i.e. north dig 17755 which links and creates the room.
Always add descriptions to doorways, and its useful in corridors to, the description 
can be seen by the player then they type: look north. To add the description you need 
to be in redit in the correct room and type:
 <dir> desc
to set a door use 
<dir> door
 
Step 6: room flags: These are rarely used, but provide useful rooms like no_magic 
rooms, but use them with care and don't ad many if any to your area.
 
Other Redit commands:
Owner: don't use this.
Create: creates a new room
?: gives help
sector: Not used much, not really needed for indoor areas (remember many ranger 
skills can only be used in forest and jungle sectors though)
format: formats the room description (you can also use .f from inside the desc)
rcopy: copies the majority of the information from one of your other rooms, useful for 
corridor sections, or large plains.
Mreset, oreset: try not to use these, you need to learn the external reset command 
(used outside redit)
Oshow, mshow useful commands to look at all objs/mobs in the area.
 
MEDIT:
Step 1, set the level of the mob, and then use autoset to standardise its stats.
 
Step 2, set the names to attack/look at the mob, i.e. 
name guard sanaria gate, this would allow you to look at it if you type look guard, 
look sanaria, look gate.
 
Step 3, set the race, use ? race for more information on what races are available, this 
sets the standard immunities, resistances and vulnerabilities.
 
Step 4, set sex, align, wealth and size. Align is between 1000 and 1000 for chaotic 
evil to lawful good. Size is important for certain skills against the mob such as shield 
bash, which tends to be size and weight orientated. Wealth is in silver (approx 100 
silver in 1 gold).
 
Step 5, set offensive behaviours: use ? off for a full list of offensive behaviours. Most 
common ones to use are dodge, parry, bash kick trip and dirt kick, depending on what 
you want your mob todo. Use fast to make the mob attack more.  Avoid using  assist_ 
Too much as it tends to cause problems when there are a lot of mobs in the room 
(problems being player deaths)
 
Step 6, set affects: use ? aff for a list of most of the affects (some haven't been added 
yet including detect_invis, detect_hidden, detect_steal and some others but they can 
still be used) common usage ones include sanc, protection evil, fly, invis, fade 
(hidden), camo, haste and pass_door. Be careful about using spells such as slow on 
the mob as this means the players cannot then cast that spell on the mob.
 
Step 7: set dam type: use ? weapon for a list of possible weapon types to use, not all 
of these will work so you may have to try a few.
 
Step 8, set short and long descriptions: short description are for when a player uses 
scan <direction> or the mob is fighting. Long descriptions are what's seen when the 
player looks in the room.
 
Step 9, description: use desc again to edit the mobs description, a minimum of 2 lines 
is required give a general description of its size, race, perhaps its claws or its 
weapons, but try to avoid things like it strikes fear into your heart unless it's a really 
really nasty mob.
 
SEE help BUILDER3
~

82 builder3~
MEDIT Other information:
Use ? act for useful things such as act sentinel stops a mob leaving its room, 
aggressive makes the mob attack all players of lower level. Use wimpy with care on 
high level mobs as it makes the mob run at 25% health, which could be an awful lot 
of chasing.
Also use act for changer (banker), shopkeepers, and healer.
 
Be careful creating hard mobs with specific weapons/damage as players can charm 
mobs that are immune to some weapons dam type (druids for instance get 4 
elementals at high level, fire elementals is immune to fire, earth is immune to lighting 
etc.)
 
OEDIT
 
Step 1: set type, use ? type for the different types, set the level and then autoarmor for 
the armor, and autoweapon for weapons.
Step 2: set name, set the names to get/ use/wear items (do not use colour here).
Step 3: Set class/race (if applicable) this sets what classes and races can wear the 
items. Use class all and race all to set all
Step 4: Set wear, you must type wear take for a person to be able to get an item from 
the ground (don't set this for things such as furniture etc. usually only 1 wear position 
is used in addition to this.
Step 5: set whether the item is to be limited. Keys are usually limited to one, so only 
one can load on the mob (keys also automatically rot after 2 ticks)
Step 6: ? extra gives the list of all extras available, use extra hum, for an item to be 
seen while blind, and extra glow for items to be seen in the dark.
Step 7:  use addaffect  to add hp/mana/hit/dam affects. As a genral guide, do not set 
hit n dam above level/10 - 1 i.e. a level 80 helm should not have more then 7/7 
hit/dam. For hp/mana it shouldn't be above level - 20, ie. Level 80 helm should not 
have more then either 60hp, or 60 mana.
Step 8: addapply does not currently work.
Step 9: add descriptions, short is what the player sees when the item is worn, long is 
what the player sees when the item is on the ground.
 
 
General notes: some people like to build the whole level first, then add mobs and 
objects, I usually build my corridor, add rooms off it, add mobs then add keys, but its 
upto you what you do, I do advise you don't lock doors until you've created the key 
for them otherwise it will get frustrating.
 
Please note, these files are only rough refrences, and not to be taken as fact.
Any errors or updates to add, please send to ALARK.
~

