1 MULTI PLAYING~
Multiplaying is defined as having more than one of your characters logged
onto the MUD at the same time, and/or having your characters interact with
one another, in any way.  As some players share IP, it can sometimes be
difficult for the Admin Staff to tell if a player is multi playing, and thus
it is requested if you share an IP with a roommate, sibling, etc. that you
write a note to 'Admin' on board 3, stating you're shared IP and which
characters belong to you, and which belong to the other player, playing
from that IP.
 
The following examples are instances of Multi Playing, and can result
in punishment:
 
- Having two of your characters logged on at the same time
- Having one of your characters logged on, while another character of
      yours is still on the mud, but left linkless.
- PKing someone that your alt is currently at war with.  This means, that
      if Alt A died to Enemy A, you couldn't log onto Alt B to exact
      vengeance upon Enemy A.
- Locating enemies with an alt, or seeing if they're currently online.
      What this means, is that you cannot log off your lvl 35 mage, and
      onto your lvl 70 prodigy, to check to see if your lvl 35 mage's
      enemy is on.  This means, don't use alts to find location of someone
      you wish to PK with an alt, nor should you log on alts to check the
      who list.
- Aiding your character with an alt.  This means:
      -Do not transfer eq between alts, whether directly or indirectly.
      -Do not powerlevel your lowbies with your highbie alt.
      -Do not go linkless with one char, log on another, to save the linkless
            char from death.
      -Best way to do this, do not allow your chars to interact in ANY SHAPE
            OR FORM.
 
Punishment for breaking Multi Playing rules can result in anything from a
slap on the wrist, to a slay.  In extreme and rare circumstances, special
punishment may be used at an Admin's disgression.
~

0 ASSISTED CHEATING~
Assisted Cheating can be described as assisting another player abuse a bug
or break the rules in any way, shape, or form.  Examples of this include:
 
- Helping a player transfer equipment between his alts.
- Helping another player abuse a bug.
- OOL assisting a player.
 
Punishment for assisting another player cheat varies in severity, with
punishment ranging from a slap on the wrist to a slay.
~

1 SPAMMING~
Spamming is repeating the same command over and over in short
succession, and is not allowed.
~

1 KINGDOM ALTS~
The Kingdom Alts rule can be described, and simply stated as: You
may *NOT* have more than one of your characters in any kingdom.
That means, only *ONE* character per player may be in any of the
existing kingdoms.
 
The reasons for this rule is as follows:
- To prevent spies, who may transfer private kingdom information via ooc.
- To keep player's alts seperate, individual, and unique.  If a player had more
      than one character in a kingdom, their character's rp would become
      intertwined, which is not allowed on this MUD.
 
Punishment for breaking the Kingdom Alts rule could result in the removal of
both of your alts from said kingdom.
~

1 LIMITS~
The Limits rule can be desribed as a character to have no more than
seven limited items within their inventory.  That means, if you type
inventory, and have eight or more limited items, you're over the limit
(be sure to check containers within your inventory as well as containers
that you are wearing).  A player may also not have more than one of the
same limited item within their inventory.   The reasons for this rule are:
 
- Preventing characters from hoarding eq.
- To try and govern the limited items possessed by players, to keep
      their possession balanced.
- To allow everyone an opportunity at some point to possess certain
      limited items.
 
There are exceptions to this rule.  Such exceptions are:
- Players are allowed to have more than one of certain pieces of
      equipment.  This includes: neck, finger, wrist, and ornament eq.
- Players are allowed to be temporarily over the limit, such as when
      wearing leveling eq.
- If you looted a corpse of a friend or acquantance, in order to return
      their eq.
 
Punishment for breaking the Limits rule can result in punishments ranging
from an Admin asking a player to choose which items to discard, until the
player is at the max limit of seven items, to an Admin seizing all limited eq
within the player's inventory.  The severity of these punishment is very
dependable on the history of the player at hand, the mood of the Admin,
and how far over the limit the was.
~

1 CHARACTER CONTROL~
Character Control can be described as the transferring of a character
to the control of another player, or simply playing a character that is not
yours.  Examples of this rule are as listed:
 
- Logging onto your friend's character for any reason.  This includes:
      - To get your own char eq.
      - To level with your own char.
      - To help your character out of a bind.
- Giving your character to another player.
      - In very rare instances, this is acceptable, and after ownership of the
            character has been transferred, it may not be transferred back or
            played by the former owner.
 
Punishment for breaking the Character Control rule varies, and usually will,
in the worst case, result in a slay.
~

0 BRUTAL DAMAGE~
