0 buildpoints~
The system is fairly straightforward.  Depending on the level
of the item, you have a variable number of points to spread
around on the bonuses.  Different types of items or bonuses
have different costs.  This is a breakdown of points vs. level.
 
LEVEL        POINTS
Newbie        4
1-5          3
6-10          6
11-15         9
16-20         12
21-25          15
26-30         18
31-35         21
36-40         24
41-45         27
46-50         30
51-55         32
56-60         34
61-65         36
66-70         38
71-75         40  
76-100        +1 point per 2 levels above 75
 
STANDARD STAT BONUSES
Bonus            Cost
+1 Stat           6 points
+3 hp/mana        1 point
+1 hit or dam     3 points
+1 to one save    3 points
 
 
For more, see "Help buildpoints2".
~

0 buildpoints2~
For armor AC bonuses:
First, use AUTOSET to set the standard AC value for
the armor.  Then, for an AC bonus, the formula is:
2 points for every 3 points of AC.  (-3 AC = 2 points, -6 = 4 points, etc.)
 
For weapon damage:
First set the weapon damage using AUTOSET, and modify it from there.
There are two values that tell how much damage a weapon does, the number
of dice and the dice size (i.e. 3d8).  You can increase either number at a
cost of 5 points for the first increase, and an additional 2 points for each
successive increase.  The first increase is 5 points, second is 7, third
is 9, and so on.  (21 points total for three increases).
 
 
Added affects for weapons:
For effects like flaming, freezing, vorpal, etc - the first affect
costs 5 points.  An additional 2 points is added to the cost
for each additional affect, same as with weapon damage.
 
 
For spell affects:
Having a permanent spell effect on a weapon is a RARE thing, and
therefore finding a weapon or armor with one should be a difficult
thing to do.  A minor spell effect is 25 points.  A minor spell is
classified as any spell that offers a modest beneficial effect, such
as ARMOR or SHIELD.  
A MAJOR spell effect costs 40 points.  Major spells are such things
as haste, spells that are common but much more powerful.
NOTE -- spells such as SANC, PROTECTION GOOD/EVIL, and the higher
level protection spells are for QUEST ITEMS ONLY.  
 
For negative bonuses:
Basically, adding a negative bonus gives points back, but at half
of the rate.  For example, a -1 DEX would only give back 3 points,
and it would require -6 HP to give a single point back.  Adding
a CURSE flag gives no points back.  Adding a negative spell, such
as poison, plague, or blind gives an additional 10 points back.
 
 
Immunities:
Immunities should never appear on standard equipment without the
consent of the Head Administrator.
~

0 addaffect~
Adding Affects can be a little tricky depending upon what you are
trying to do.  But if you are wanting to add stats, hp, mana, etc. 
To your items this is the way to do it.  
 
Syntax:  addaffect [location] [#xmod]
 
The location is the affect taht you are wanting to add.
 
Valid affects are:
none               strength           dexterity          intelligence       
wisdom             constitution       mana               hp                   move               ac                 hitroll            damroll             saves              savingpara         savingrod          savingpetri        savingbreath       savingspell        spellaffect        
 
#xmod is the number at which you want to add.  Example:
 
Addaff Strength 2 - would add 2 strength stat points to a piece of
equipment.  Remember that you can add negative affects as well as
positive affects.
~

